problems: Landowner was originally looking for recommendations for a logger but after viewing his woods, it was apparent that it had already been high-graded about 25 years ago.  What remained were a few larger trees spaced far apart with many smaller trees that were sapling or log timber sized. The canopy was mostly closed but if there was an additional harvest, invasives would be introduced and forest regeneration might not occur.  We suggested the landowner work with a forester (I gave him information from DEC about finding a forester as well as the logs to lumber fact sheer; Jonathan to send him two names) to improve the health of the existing lot prior to the removal of more trees.  There were lots of grapevines, bittersweet and honeysuckle on the property.  Since the landowner did not live there (and hadn’t visited the site in quite some time), we suggested he have a conversation with his children regarding what they wanted to do with the land prior to considering any forest management or potential subdivision or property sale.
thoughts: It was great to team with Jonathan Farber again.  His experience is so helpful but my experience on the Catskill Town Planning Board also was helpful as we discussed what it would take to subdivide the parcel..  The amount of invasive species around the edge of the property (along the road) was considerable but further inland, grape vine was the only problem that was widely evident.  The landowner had not visited the property in some time and his limited mobility was problematic as the site was very hilly.  That’s why we spent so much time talking him through legacy planning options to figure out his objectives for the property to best determine the path forward.

other_why_detail: This is a very small "woodlot" that surrounds the  owner's primary residence. It offers privacy and shade,  as well as the opportunity to garden and bird watch
problems: Owner seeks an ethical, qualified arborist (rather than a forester) with whom he can establish and execute a tree management plan.  Owner has expressed frustration sorting through the plethora of information on the Internet to find reliable, appropriate material to address his issues.  MFO Volunteer to follow up with links to various reliable resources including Japanese knotweed management information.
action_other: Owner is likely to arrange for  arborists to visit property to establish and execute a tree management plan.
thoughts: I suggest that more owners of  suburban woodlots would find, and benefit from,  the  resources available through Forest Connect if they better understood that the  trees surrounding their residences can be considered woodlots.  Such small patches of trees are most often referred to as back- or side- yards, rarely woodlots, and never forests.      Consequently, it is difficult for the average suburban "backyard" tree owner who visits the CCE website to  understand that  the way to access resources is by first selecting  "Environment" then picking "Forest Connect".  (https://cals.cornell.edu/cornell-cooperative-extension/our-work/environment).   Since the challenges backyard  owners face are often similar to those that  apply to larger woodlots/forests just on a much smaller scale, they could only benefit from connecting to Forest Connect (pun intended).   Please consider expanding the picks  on the CCE website to include a category for "Backyard" tree/woodlot owners and expanding the conversation to acknowledge these owners share some common concerns.  Thanks,

problems: this is a wonderful working landscape -- the owner cuts and sells hay from the field and firewood from the woodlot all by himself.  the key issue we discussed is estate planning. i advised that the family talk together and come up with a plan -- do their adult and off-site son and daughter want to keep it? will they sell and when? would they consider talking about an easement with a land trust? this property is top notch.  the views to the northern escarpment of the catskills are superb, and it is well set up as a working farm with fenced pastures,  and a number of well maintained barns. we also discussed the pros and cons of a timber harvest now and i recommended calling in two local consulting foresters for their opinions.  invasive species presence is very low compared to most forest i have visited -- japanese stiltgrass is established along the extensive trails through the property but has so far kept to the track. emerald ash borer is taking out the last of the ash.

thoughts: I spent 90 minutes on the property with the owner who just purchased the land two months ago.  It is primarily a well established maple stand with some pine trees. The canopy is mostly closed with little sign to new tree growth.  A great number of the mature trees have bittersweet vines growing on them, so we talked about managing them as well as the barberry, poison ivy, and other invasive plants on the woodlot.  The owner hopes to build a house some day (10+ years from now) and just want to keep the land ‘healthy’ in the interim.  In addition to talking about invasives, we talked about creating brush piles for wildlife, keeping snags for birds, protecting the vernal pools, creating trails, and id resources. He welcomed the multiple fact sheets I left with him as well as the list of DEC Cooperating Foresters that he plans to review and find one to work with.  It was a great site for my first solo woods walk.

thoughts: The owners are planning on building a house at the top of a ridge. We discussed bringing in soil and the possibility of bringing in invasive species. We advised the owners to ask any builders to clean their equipment before coming to the property to help keep out invasive specie. Even though there was evidence of deer on the property the understory was very healthy and vibrant and the mix of trees was extremely diverse. This kind of property is getting increasingly rare in Columbia County. The owners would like to create flower and vegetable gardens around the property but keep the rest of the property in its natural state.

action_other: Complete building projects and pick a natural wooded area to show case it to promote further forest improvements; old barn area.
thoughts: This property is currently an active construction site. They are getting ready to start putting up buildings and platforms. Of the 195 acres less than half is forested with typical mixed hardwoods found in the Hudson Valley. The forest edge has typical early successional habitat; birch, cherry, maples and pines. The oaks dominate the forest cover as you venture further into the forest. The property has bittersweet and multiflora along the edges that need to be managed. At this time they do not have a plan on how to control invasive species, establish and maintain forest trails, conduct TSI, regeneration nor have they identified the wildlife habitat they wish to establish to attract the species they wish to promote. They have a lot on their plate currently and need to seek assistance from local natural resource professionals, local land trust and conservation groups. I recommend they begin partnering with Columbia Land Conservancy, join NYFOA & attend webinars.

problems: Control of interfering vegetation, particularly honeysuckle which is growing aggressively on many parts of the property.
thoughts: Mr. Yokokawa and his parents bought their property in 2022.  They have limited experience managing a woodlot and are eager to learn. Their longer term plan is to build a cabin or home on the property and raise organic vegetables, although these plans are in the preliminary stage at this time.  The property is composed of 146 total acres. Approximately 80 of these acres are wooded.  The woodlot is a mix of hard and soft maple, cherry, hemlock, white pine, aspen, and some apple trees. Mr Yokokawa commented that there are no oak trees on the property and is interested in planting oaks and other northeastern tree species to add to forest diversity. There is quite a bit of honeysuckle on the property along with some multiflora rose.  Mr. Yokokawa indicated he and his family members wish to employ organic woodlot management and farming principles and will attempt to control the honeysuckle by mechanical means such as repeated brush-hogging. MFOs confirmed that they can be available to the Yokokawas for follow-on questions and support.

problems: the landowner was exclusively interested in two mature trees adjacent to his house -- a white pine that died and was removed by an arborist and a white oak in severe decline.  both were in the path of construction equipment that dug a pond on the property.  the excavation contractor ran equipment and added several feet of fill within the dripline of these trees.  i recommended the owner call an arborist to remove the oak tree to protect his house. the landowner was not interested in walking the woods.
thoughts: this visit and my previous mfo visit to robert capone were both with landowners solely focused on a few trees in decline adjacent to their houses.  this is alright with me and in both cases i feel the meetings were useful. these two back-to-back visits were the only times i have met with landowners who were not at all interested in walking their woods... just thought you should know! in neither case was the reason for the requested visit described on the intake form or in the follow-up emails to schedule the meetings.

problems: Their spruce trees are in decline, as are their neighbor's which I also visited when I was there. We discussed diagnostic resources to confirm and resources for supporting tree health including possible thinning. We also spoke about their road (they are in a private community and it is a road owned and maintained by their HOA) which is experiencing significant erosion, Suislaw Model Forest BMPs, the MFO program, and the upcoming woods walk at Suislaw. They are interested in speaking with an arborist next; I offered to provide a list of names.
action_other: They intend to submit samples of the damaged trees for diagnosis and a soil sample to determine steps to take to support tree health. They are interested in learning more about erosion control for their road. They plan to speak with the HOA about having another MFOV visit to examine the larger area since many spruce trees in the community are in decline.
thoughts: This was a tree health visit, not a typical MFOV visit. They have small acreage, 2.5 acres of woods. They are seasonal residents and appreciated learning about all the resources available. As a Master Gardener as well, I treated this more like an MG call, to help diagnose a plant health problem and offer possible solutions. I chose to visit and invest the time in order to connect with what seems to me to be an emerging audience: new residents/second homeowners who want to learn more about their land and the resources available as they experience the stressors and effects of climate change and insect and pest pressure on their trees. They are part of and HOA and plan to speak at an upcoming meeting about the MFO program and see if there is interest in a neighborhood visit which would touch a number of people and much more acreage. Theirs is a private road with some steep sections and a great deal of erosion during these storms we are getting so I told them about the BMPs as to share with the HOA as they speak to contractors about re-doing the road. Now that they know about CCE I suspect they will avail themselves of more educational opportunities.

town: Forest Porperty is located at forty nine Engel Rd Austerliz New York
other_why_detail: Extremely Important To protect nature or biological diversity To pass land on to my children or other heirs
problems: Manage ferns
action_other: Build a house and an access road
thoughts: I love my woodland because it allows me to enjoy nature and wildlife. I own my woodland primarily for recreation, relaxation, and the natural beauty of the woods.  <<MFO comments>> You have a property that was pretty clear from the usual invasive plants that we see in Northeastern Columbia County. The invasives common up here in the Northeastern part of the county are the Japanese stilt grass, autumn olive, multiflora rose and oriental bittersweet. Most of the time these seeds travel on tires, and peoples’ shoes so it is necessary to be vigilant.  Your first comments to us were that you wished to understand your property better. I have included links to various resources available to you, including those you received as hard copy from Shane, and hope that they are helpful.  For the purposes of discussion, I'd like to segregate your property into the area where we entered the property (lowlands) and the area where you plan to put up the house (higher plateau). The lowlands cover the area of the former logging road and is a slightly lower elevation and the higher land is south of the creek that runs through the property. The land near the logging road was wet with an abundance of ferns, which flourish in damp, rich soil. The rest of the property was wooded, though not too heavily because it had been logged periodically. The loggers seem to have taken care of the land harvesting a variety of trees and leaving  a variety of trees behind. You have hardwoods (oak, maples) and some valuable timber such as black cherry. There are also eastern pine and birches interspersed among these trees. You do not appear to have stands of one particular species.  The first question you had was about ticks. Ticks are, as you know, ubiquitous this year because of the relatively mild winter we had. It is best to protect yourselves. You were wearing wellingtons, which is a good thing. It is best to have a couple of sets of clothing (pants and long sleeved shirt), your hats, gloves, and shoes sprayed with permethrin (Sawyer Products SP657 Premium Permethrin Insect Repellent for Clothing, Gear & Tents, Trigger Spray, sold at Amazon). Allow clothing to dry and wash hands well after use as this is a toxic product. This treatment is good for about 6 washes. Information about ticks and tick- borne diseases https://www.cdc.gov/ticks/tickbornediseases/tickID.html,  https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2021/06/11/well/tick-disease-lyme.html?action=click&pgtype=Article&state=default&module=styln-ticks&variant=show&region=BELOW_MAIN_CONTENT&block=storyline_flex_guide_recirc Please feel free to go to your local government sites as well.  Forest Age and Maturity: Shane and I reviewed your intake form to address any specifics you might want covered. Our assumption was that for many years your land was part of a larger parcel of forested land and had not been used for crop production probably due to the presence of wet areas/wetlands. Our guess that it was probably used for timber production under section 480-a of the Real Property Tax Law when it was part of a larger piece of land.  Most of your property has a combination of hardwoods. There is some infiltration of witch hazel that grows about 6-8 ft tall and spreads out tending to shade out younger plants and not allow robust new growth. These are some of the bushes you might want to cull. Our main concern is that throughout the property, there is very little understory regeneration of trees. It is what folks at Cornell describe as an "even-aged" forest. The trees are maybe 50-60 years old and in some cases may be older. There appeared to be a stone wall which suggests that there may have been a farm for crops or livestock many years ago. However, based on the lack of quick growing trees or invasives this may not be an accurate conclusion. This presumption can be easily confirmed with some searching of the Agricultural Census schedule data that farmers were required to complete in mid-19th century. If you are curious just ask. More reading material: https://smallfarms.cornell.edu/2022/10/anticipating-the-next-forest-ecology-and-management-for-sustaining-forests/  Stewardship Plan: otherwise known as David and Roberta’s to-do list. We think it is helpful to plan out proposed landscape level changes by breaking them out into bite-sized projects.   We would suggest starting with the area of your proposed building site. In the meantime, try to keep your loppers (and electric chainsaw? Chainsaw safety: http://ccecolumbiagreene.org/family-consumer-sciences/family-economics-community-resiliency/emergency-preparedness/chainsaw-safety) handy to remove any unwanted species.  For ease of tractor access, I would probably start on the logging road. It is best to convert this road into your driveway as it has been drivable, and the relative pitch is gradual.  The building site (higher land): This area has some valuable trees. It may be a good idea to get a forester to harvest them and give you some cash or use it as payment for assessing the rest of your property. This may be something you should do sooner rather than later so you can benefit from them. They will probably grade the area as well.  The lower area is populated with ferns. This may be an ideal spot to plant some trees. You can use the USDA soil survey map to determine which trees will do well. Your property's Soil Map from the USDA-NRCS. (https://websoilsurvey.sc.egov.usda.gov/app/WebSoilSurvey.aspx)  You can get an idea about the type of soil in your particular area, if you decide to add trees.  Perspective on Tree Growth should you choose to plant in the lowlands (see caveat under "water control") Willow: You have already planted one in the wet area. They do well in wet areas and are fast growing. Some of the other trees are listed below:  The ferns are invasive and hard to eradicate especially if the land continues to be wet. One would have to use a herbicide. I would suggest some trees be planted in the area where the ferns currently are. Planting a tree forces clearing the ground of ferns and digging a large enough hole to put in a young tree. Some of the trees for wet areas are suggested below. In addition, you can also plant hardwoods that are already present on your property in areas where there is a lack of trees. The aim is to have trees of varying ages so you have a ground story with grasses, (if the sunlight reaches it), a middle story with younger trees and an upper story with mature trees.  Black Walnut: should you ever decide to embark on adding trees, this species could be good for the lower land where the ferns are plentiful because (1) it is nut-bearing, thus positive for wildlife; (2) it grows well in rich alluvial soils; (3) it is allelopathic, keeps invasives at bay (via its juglone chemical), but do not put your vegetable garden near it; (4) it makes beautiful flooring, should you want to take one of them down for Black Walnut flooring for your daughter's house in 30 years.  Silver Maple: Can be planted in a swampish area and is a fast grower. Sycamore: Another fast grower and does not mind wet feet.  Apart from the hardwoods on your property you have black cherry trees. These trees do not mind wet feet either and are monetarily valuable to grow. They would make great furniture/cabinet material if you ever decided to harvest them. Be aware that these trees may suffer from Gummosis -- Black Cherry trees ooze a dark gelatinous substance from their bark, which often happens when they are stressed, for example when there is an extremely dry spell.  All of the above listed trees need full sunlight and should grow well if there is no competition and might reduce the harm being done by ferns. As you get more familiar with trees, you can add sugar maple (a stand of them can provide maple syrup) and burr oak could also prosper in wettish areas.  Mushroom cultivation: You expressed a wish to grow mushrooms and ginseng on your property. The Cornell Cooperative Extension of Columbia/Greene County has classes offered periodically throughout the year. You need a water source and shade, which you have in the area near the stream, for growing shitake. A source of hardwood logs too is required and you should keep that in mind when trees are being demolished for your house. You can find the courses offered on the right-hand side of the web page. https://ccecolumbiagreene.org/. If you get on their email list, they will send you monthly reminders.  Water control: You have a stream that runs through your property. You would like to enlarge it so that you have a stream that runs more or less throughout the year and not only during the early spring. You would need to determine where the source of the water is so that you know if your source of water is clean. If it is, then you can perhaps have a little pond that will provide some resource for the birds.  Invasive parasites and other dead trees:   Emerald Ash Borer... Impossible to mitigate at this stage. If you have ash trees (we did not note any) they tend to die off in this area from the emerald ash borer incursion. Ash can be used for firewood or standing snag as shelter for animals. It is sometimes useful to keep standing dead trees, they are a haven for birds and small mammals and insects and provide a food source.  Invasive Plants: Although you had no invasive plants that we could see, this information will help if you see invasives appear. The entire following video link is excellent.   I find it helpful and somewhat complete from the acknowledged expert in the area of invasives control at Penn State U Ag Extension, Dave Jackson.  Identifying and Controlling Invasive Plants on Forestland If you choose to 'cut to the chase' (again) below are the relevant time points in the video for you:  Japanese Stiltgrass is at 14:00 of the video.  Oriental Bittersweet at 33:38.  Japanese Barberry at 42:13.  Honeysuckle at 43:57 Tree of Heaven at 50:28  Government Assistance--  (a) The NYS Trees for Tribs program—If you want to keep the wet areas from erosion, this program helps. Twenty-five trees given to you, if your application is approved. Need to apply first. https://www.dec.ny.gov/animals/77710.html  If you have questions, you may email them at TreesForTribs@dec.ny.gov or call them at (518) 402-94  DEC Regenerate NY Forestry Cost Share Program. You pay 20% of the total bill. You will need to hire/designate a forester and have a plan. Minimum grant from NYS is $10,000 which means your minimum cost under the program is $2,500 on a bill of $12,500. This is granted as a first come, first serve process and stops when the money runs out. Project can take 3 years; so you can amortize your outlay. They have an approved list of contractors to do the work. https://www.dec.ny.gov/lands/119950.html   There are chainsaw classes held by a forester named Bill Lindoff. The class is called Game of Logging. He can be reached at either of these links. If he cannot help you with the clearing of trees at you house site, you can ask him for a recommendation. If you draw a blank there, you can go to the DEC list and pick someone who lives closest to you. http://www.gameoflogging.com/  This site offers many classes, and it is worth attending these classes to learn about chainsaw safety. https://www.nycamh.org/programs-and-services/game-of-logging.php  There are also chainsaw classes for women taught at the Cornell Cooperative Extension taught by Tracey Testo.  The class for women carries the same name.  (c) The DEC Saratoga Nursery sells trees every year at great prices, typically starting in January. The good stuff goes quickly, so you need to keep your eye out on their site. Here's is the link for the 2022 sale back in January:  https://www.dec.ny.gov/animals/75799.html  (d) Sales of trees take place each year, in the counties...by the County Soil and Water Conservation Districts, at discounted prices. Specifically Albany, Columbia and Greene counties recently. The Soil and water conservation is administered by people who are also members of the Cornell Cooperative extension. Soil and Water Conservation District | Albany County, NY

mfo_name: Teresa Golden with Peter Paden and Kieran Fagan
problems: Landowner was interested in developing the forest for ‘forest bathing’ and looking for short term income producing options to help fun work to develop trails, etc. to support this idea. Spent time explaining the length of time associated with commercial production of ginseng and mushrooms.  Property had been recently logged so there was no justification to have a timber harvest.
thoughts: The forest itself was in good shape with good diversity and tree age, and the canopy was thin enough to enable sunlight to reach the forest floor.  There was Japanese stilt grass on the forest trails so we discussed the need to control it o avoid it spreading into the forest. There were many invasive plants leading into the forest including autumn olive, wild grape, multi flora rose, etc, so we provided materials to educate her on how to control these to avoid spread into the woods.  She is looking for companies that could do some ot this work including maintains the trails.  A list of vetted companies by county would be helpful to aid landowners in this regard.  Going with two other (newbie) MFOs was helpful as we all provided different perspectives to help answer her questions. Note the Peter Paden (prpaden@gmail,com) is from Columbia County and Kieran Fagan (Kieranfagan711@gmail,com) is from Dutchess County.  The form did not allow their names or e-mail addresses to be included.  As i traveled the greatest distance to get there, I entered my mileage and time into this form.

problems: There is one diseased White Pine Tree in the midst of a larger stand of very healthy White Pines. Owner is concerned of disease spread to healthy trees. Disease appears to be the result of White Pine Blister Rust, but the onset has takenb place more quickly than research predicts for WPBR. I am putting the owner in touch with Kelsey McLaughlin at the DEC Forest Diagnostic Lab. Kelsey believes it may be the result of  Caliciopsis Pinea fungus.
thoughts: Caliciopsis Pines fungal pathogen on Eastern White Pine Trees is something I have fist become aware. Apparently recent in the last 5 yeasr or more???

thoughts: Dan and Erika have done a lot right in the short period they've owned the property. They have marked their boundaries with posted signs and paint, they have worked with a forester to develop a management plan, and have contacted DEC regarding the development of a 480A plan. We walked the property - a beautiful parcel only half a mile down the road from my house! Their main areas of focus for the visit were to discuss tree identification (we went through a key and identified the main hardwood species, plus willow, aspen etc), identifying and managing interfering vegetation (multi-flora rose, hawthorn, honeysuckle and, unfortunately, japanese knotweed), and some basics about pests and diseases (EAB, beech bark disease, beech leaf disease). In each case I emphasized that there are resources available to help them learn about these topics, and I shared several pdfs and URLs that I'd been given during my training.

In this case, "Healthy Forests for Our Future", "Technical Guide to Crop Tree Release in Hardwood Forests", "Grading Hardwood Trees: A Guide..." and Crop Tree Management in Eastern Hardwoods". These were selected  by the owner. I also bring books. They can take note of those that are of interest.

Mr. Hughes was very interested in learning distinction of hardwood, softwood, conifer and deciduous.  By the end of the walk he could identify the dominant Hemlock, Yellow Birch and Poplar.

problems: Owner is interested primarily in regeneration of better tree stock, possibly walnut or maple species, to replace the aspen and dying ash that make up the bulk of species on the property. There were fewer than a dozen total oak and black cherry trees in an even-aged 30-40 year old stand of aspen, with about 20 even-height pines mixed throughout. Only one timber grade oak existed, and the owner recognized it's special status and value as a keeper. There was a mixture of same-age red maples and a few sugar maples, and we discussed small syrup hobby operations. There is poor drainage in wet season, poor water availability in dry season, and high deer pressure. The owner does not burn wood, and there is no vehicle access to the small woodlot.  We discussed creating another one or two trails into the center of the woodlot, we discussed the presence of a nice vernal pool and the biodiversity that might be observed there, and the owners seemed especially interested in the idea of clearing a small half-acre area of buckthorn/autumn olive/honeysuckle mix to make room for some protected tree seedlings. We discussed creating a water supply to that area by laying an over-ground black vinyl pipe from the house along a new path. The owner had disappointing results from a previous attempt at regeneration with tube/seedlings, apparently because of drought and deer pressure. I sent the owner links to historical aerial photography from the Cornell archives, and discussed geolocation and mapping of individual trees on the property, as well as the DEC annual tree and shrub sale.

other_why_detail: Zach wants to develop a cider operation and nut farm.
problems: Zach owns a very small, 3.5 acres, of woods, most of which is covered by invasive plants, with lots of buckthorn and honeysuckle. Zach wants to plant lots of apple and nut trees, has a nice field of about 6 acres where he could plant things. Could gain additional land for planting his crop trees if he removed invasive plants. Has a small amount of forest land, most of which is dying ash, which he wants to cut for firewood. Requested information about using deer fencing for his field, which would be much cheaper in the long-term compared to trying to protect individual trees. Will provide Zach with some contacts in the New York Nut Growers Association who have experience with fencing large areas to keep out deer. Zach is not really interested in forestry with the small amount of wooded land that he has, most of which will be cut down for firewood.

other_why_detail: Subject is a suburban lot having young (13yrs) maples in a stressed condition--met with owner--took photos of conditions then researched potential issues and reported back to owner-- recommended a local arborist but feeling is that trees may not recover.
problems: See above for information
thoughts: Another referral from the Master Gardeners program at our local CCE.   Would recommend ALL MFO's and the program cooperate with Master Gardeners as many property owners are unsure who to contact first with forestry issues.

problems: NA
thoughts: Owners have limited ability to identify plants and that will be a handicap in achieving some of their management objectives.  We discussed a wide range of issues.

problems: what invasive plants are there and how to manage them
thoughts: Owner is not sure of what he wants to do with the property. I mentioned that I was doing a shiitake mushroom workshop for CCE the following day and he came to that. He had tried growing mushrooms before without success. Since he lives within a few miles from my house, I told him to stop by if he had additional thoughts/questions about his plans.

other_detail: previous owner told him to contact CCE for information
problems: Owner has many plans for different portions of the woods, some of which may involve harvest. Since he has had the property for a short time, plans may evolve, expand, or change. Owner seems very knowledgeable about many aspects of managing his property, has recently installed a large pond, and has an extensive train network. Trail maintenance is an issue to work on.
thoughts: Owner recently completed the MFO training and is planning to become active in visiting other woodlot owners. He is very well versed in many areas of forestry, tree ID, and he is an avid steward of his land.

problems: different sections of the woods have different problems/attributes. We talked about the plusses and minuses of different stands and how to go about improving or handling them.
action_other: motivated to get started and learn as much as possible. As experience increases, various plans will unfold.
thoughts: Both individuals recently trained as MFOs and are eager to get started visiting other forest owners. They realize that they have a lot to learn and experience, but they are willing and are highly motivated. They wanted an MFO visit in part to see how it is done.

problems: NA
thoughts: Her family has owned the property for about 60 years and she has enjoyed it and planted plantation pine on part of it as a youth. Her older brother owns the property but is uninvolved and lets her use it as she wishes. She expects to inherit the property if he does not just give it to her ahead of time. She wants to learn everything she can about forest stewardship, with an emphasis on habitat improvement. She will retain a consultant to develop a plan. Most of the forest needs TSI.    23-217

problems: Craig came to visit our place in Tompkins County to learn about how we were harvesting trees and operating a sawmill. Went out to our red pine stand and demonstrated the use of the Farmi winch to set up a hitch of 5 logs to bring back to sawmill site. Bucked logs at sawmill site and moved logs into sawmill building. Then reviewed safe operation of sawmill with Craig, demonstrated the sawing of 1 log with Craig and then let Craig saw his first log. Craig would like to set up a sawmill operation on his land in Cuba, NY. Have continued to answer Craig's questions about sawmill operations through emails and Zoom calls. Craig will retire in a couple of years and wants to get set up to saw logs after retirement. Has some conifer plantations to harvest. Suggested that Craig take GOL and Craig has joined NYFOA.
thoughts: For some specific topics, it is useful to have the landowner travel to an MFO volunteer's location to be able to actually demonstrate and practice the skills that the landowner would like to learn.

problems: The owners want to remove large mature invasive species from the open area in their property to gain access to the wooded part of their property. They are interested in enlarging the meadows to  accommodate beekeeping, gardening and fruit/nut trees to increase the diversity of the species on their property. Then, they would like to turn their attention to timber improvement cuts, thinning, etc.
thoughts: These particular owners. like many others, need information and training on tools and techniques to tackle invasive species infestations on their property. They would like to know how to buy and use a chainsaw, walk-behind rotary cutter, small tractor and implements and so forth. I have invited them to the property that my wife Alice and I manage, to observe and try using the tools that we use to achieve results similar to those that they desire.

problems: Owner needs to ponder:  he is doing things to bring in deer (apple trees, feed plots) but has deer impact to forest.
action_other: Interested in MFO program.  Started with 2023 class but unable to complete.
thoughts: This was our first visit and we felt well prepared with all the basic information (or at least knew where to send the woods owner for info).   Being able to identify trees/shrubs seems to be an important skill that lends credibility to what we have to say.  Not our strong point but are working on!

problems: This was a rather unique visit. We looked at several trees on the property and talked about basic tree biology, competition among trees for needed resources, proper pruning and maintenance of lawn trees; selection of appropriate species for the landscape and the property. This was more of an "urban forestry/homeowner interest" visit, rather than the typical forest visit by an MFO.
thoughts: Please see comments above. Homeowner obviously loves trees much more than an average property owner, and wants the best possible for outcome for each of the dozen or so trees we looked at and talked about. Additionally, they want to plant trees that blend in with the surrounding area, but ones that also offer added privacy.

other_why_detail: Landowner wants to leave this land to his son and grandson who have an active interest in the land.
problems: Th owner has. been enthusiastically approached by a forester and feels a bit pushed. The owner decided to let this forster talk to his son, so that his son can explain that they are not interested at this time in any harvesting. The Forster he spoke to mentioned cutting diseased Beech and harvesting some lumber. The owner is not financially pressed  and does not want to do a harvesting.
action_other: The owner's son and grandson are likely going to take the Game of Logging course. Th owner will probably become a member of NYFOA. The owner wants to have a management plan drawn up and locate a DEC Cooperating Forester. As this is a three generation enterprise, the son and grandson may pursue some entreprenurial projects or EQIP conservation projects.
thoughts: Although this owner thought maybe he should get a forest thinning, he reallydid not know what that would mean or whether he could do this himself or not. The owner does not live on the property and mainly wants to preserve it for the next generation and use it for hunting and enjoyment. The owner repeatedly asked, "What if I just. do nothing?" Th owner was encouraged to make an appointment with a DEC forester who could assess the issues with the property and trees. There is an. old sugar shack on the property and many mature maples. The owner's son and grandson might bee interested int maple sugaring. There are large patches of fern growth within the forest and many damaged trees and dangling branches. The owner was not sure if this was something he could deal with himself or should hav e dealt with professionally.

problems: Property has long frontage along Au Sable River. He has worked with Au Sable River Assoc. Will be doing bank stabilization and wetland creation. Will be doing softening of hard edges along field. Sources of native trees and shrubs. Will plant native wild flowers. Wishes to cut some sawtimber for person use projects.
thoughts: Handouts are critical for visits. I give all forest owners  a few bulletins and ForestConnect factsheets depending on their interests and back copies of NY Forest Owner magazine.  Also hand out tree scale stick and give quick lesson. Also inform them of additional sources of assistance such as agencies and organizations. Is that fact sheet listing all still available? This report form should also include "creation of wetlands", not just ponds.

problems: Owner very knowledgeable regarding agroforestry options and maple production. BMPs for erosion control discussed. will contact DEC regarding regeneration program.
action_other: Will be buying shrubs from DEC nursery.

thoughts: Novice woodland owner with very limited knowledge of the trees on the property and the woodland environment.  evidence of very unsound chainsaw operation, leaving dangerous half sawed trees hanging. Beech-Hemlock forest, with heavy impacts of beech-bark disease, and wooly adelgid. Ash trees all impacted by EAB, many dead--some around the house.  I encouraged he get professional help to remove trees.  Good wildlife in area, we saw turkey and deer while walking the property.  Also evidence of bear.  Property is on a hilltop in Helderbergs with limestone out-cropping and some springs, ponds and streams cut through the property.  Some sugar and red maples, a few oaks, none more than 10 inches dbh.  I encouraged him to think about a management plan, or to at least write down his objectives for the property.
